### OpenCV for Windows 11 (GCC / MSYS2) ###

Ready-to-use build scripts for compiling OpenCV C++ projects on Windows 11 using the MSYS2 UCRT64 GCC toolchain — no MSVC required (visual studio from microsoft).

## Preface
The official OpenCV pre-built binaries are designed from MSVC and will produce linker errors when used with GCC. 
If you want to build OpenCV C++ projects with GCC on Windows, you need to compile OpenCV from source first. These scripts automate that entire process.

## Contents
`build_opencv.sh` | Builds OpenCV from source using GCC + Ninja (run once)
`build.sh` | Configures and builds your project against the GCC-compiled OpenCV

## Prerequisites
### 1.1. c\c++ compiler (MSYS2 ucrt64)
### 1.2. cmake
### 1.3. ninja

run these command in git\bash terminal for updates dependencies
```bash
pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-gcc
pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-cmake
pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-ninja
```
Add `C:\msys64\ucrt64\bin` to your Windows system `PATH`.

### 2. Download OpenCV Source
Download OpenCV 4.12.0 source from [https://opencv.org/releases](https://opencv.org/releases) and extract it to:

## Quick Start
### Step 1 — Build OpenCV from Source (run once)

From any MSYS2 or Git Bash terminal:
```bash
bash build_opencv.sh
```
This will configure, compile, and install OpenCV to `C:\Users\USER\opencv\install_mingw`. This step takes several minutes.

### Step 2 — Add OpenCV DLLs to PATH (run once)

Add the following to your Windows system `PATH` so compiled executables can find the DLLs at runtime:
```
C:\Users\USER\opencv\install_mingw\x64\mingw\bin
```

### Step 3 — Build Your Project

```bash
bash build.sh
```

### Step 4 — Run

```bash
./build/opencv_app.exe
```

---

## Project Structure

```
your_project/
├── OpenCV.cc           ← your source file
├── CMakeLists.txt
├── build_init/
|    └───build.sh
|    └───build_opencv.sh
└── .vscode/
    └── settings.json   ← IntelliSense config for VS Code
```

 to use, modify, and distribute.
